## Think Critically

:::evaluate{criteria="os-design"}

### Why an OS in Jack?

The entire OS is written in Jack, the same high-level language as user programs. What are the implications of this design choice? How does it differ from a real-world OS?

### Criteria
- Notes that a Jack-written OS is simpler and more portable than assembly
- Recognizes performance costs of a high-level OS
- Connects to the pedagogical goal: students can understand and modify the entire system
:::

## Project

:::project{environment="node" template="nand2tetris-project12"}

### Objective

Implement the Jack OS standard library — all 8 modules.

### Requirements
1. Implement Math (multiply, divide, sqrt using efficient algorithms)
2. Implement String (constructors, concatenation, comparison, substring)
3. Implement Array (new, dispose)
4. Implement Output (character and string printing to screen)
5. Implement Screen (pixels, lines, rectangles, circles)
6. Implement Keyboard (key press detection, character reading)
7. Implement Memory (heap initialization, alloc, deAlloc using free list)
8. Implement Sys (init, halt, error, wait, timer)

### Hints
- Free list management: each free block stores a pointer to the next block and its size
- Multiplication: use shift-and-add (repeated shifting + conditional addition)
- Screen: character glyphs are stored as 11x16 bitmaps in a hardcoded array
- Test each OS module individually with the supplied test programs before integration
- The OS tests are the most demanding — they require all modules to work together correctly
:::
